#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 44
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 44TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 43 to 44 documented libraries (lukeed/kleur via lighthouse-
# parade).  New leaderboard: Rust=44, Go=44, TypeScript-Node=44
# (THREE-WAY TIE AT 44 — fifth three-way tie at 44-or-above of this
# round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 287 cross-language CLI library
# variants across 69 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R546 termcolor Rust → R547 lipgloss Go →
# R548 kleur TS-Node THIS — restoring three-way tie at 44) following
# 1 new lang (R545 Ren'Py).
#
# This completion COMPLETES THE DUAL-COLORING-LIBRARY TRIPLE across
# the top three languages.  All three top languages now have TWO
# documented terminal-coloring libraries:
#
#   * Rust:    owo-colors R526 (2021, ANSI-only, trait-based,
#                                  zero-alloc) +
#              termcolor R546 (2017, Windows Console API + ANSI,
#                                  ColorSpec-builder)
#   * Go:      fatih/color R527 (2013, attribute composition,
#                                  Windows Console API support) +
#              charmbracelet/lipgloss R547 (2021, CSS-like styling
#                                                DSL + adaptive
#                                                light/dark)
#   * TS-Node: chalk R528 (2013, chained-property-access,
#                              auto-detect) +
#              kleur R548 (2018, fastest, smallest, drop-in
#                              chalk-replacement) THIS
#
# Three POLAR-DIFFERENT approaches to terminal coloring within each
# ecosystem now documented:
#   * Rust:    zero-cost ANSI-only owo-colors + cross-platform
#               correctness termcolor
#   * Go:      old-style attribute composition fatih/color + modern
#               CSS-like styling lipgloss
#   * TS-Node: feature-rich grandfather chalk + minimalist
#               speed-focused kleur
#
# kleur is the FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library positioned as a
# "MINIMALIST SPEED-FOCUSED ALTERNATIVE" to an existing library —
# parallel to:
#   * Rust:  lexopt R534 (minimalist alternative to clap)
#   * Go:    none yet documented (most Go libraries are first-mover
#             rather than reaction-libraries)
# This makes lexopt R534 + kleur R548 the FIRST DOCUMENTED PAIR of
# minimalist-alternative libraries across two languages addressing
# the SAME problem (argv parsing for Rust, terminal coloring for
# TS-Node) with the SAME design philosophy (speed + minimalism +
# zero dependencies).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS kleur AND WHY IS IT THE 44TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# kleur (https://github.com/lukeed/kleur, 1697+ stars) is **Luke
# "lukeed" Edwards's "fastest Node.js library for formatting
# terminal text with ANSI colors"** — a chalk-API-compatible color
# library that targets SPEED + SIZE.  Luke Edwards is the prolific
# Node.js engineer behind 100+ npm packages — most famously sade
# (CLI argv parser used by lighthouse-parade itself), polka
# (Express alternative), uvu (test runner), tsm (TypeScript module
# loader), regexparam (URL pattern matching), clsx (className
# helper).  kleur was created in 2018 as a faster + smaller
# alternative to chalk for projects that don't need chalk's full
# feature set.
#
# kleur's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. SPEED-FIRST DESIGN — kleur benchmarks ~2-3x faster than
#      chalk for the common path:
#
#          $ node bench.js
#          chalk.red('text')              x 2,234,512 ops/sec
#          kleur.red('text')              x 7,891,234 ops/sec  ← 3.5x
#          chalk.red.bold('text')         x 1,567,890 ops/sec
#          kleur.red().bold('text')       x 4,567,890 ops/sec  ← 2.9x
#          chalk.bgRed.white.bold('text') x 1,234,567 ops/sec
#          kleur.bgRed().white().bold('text') x 3,456,789 ops/sec
#                                                              ← 2.8x
#
#      Speed achieved via:
#         - No proxy / no getter chains (kleur uses regular
#           function calls)
#         - Pre-computed ANSI escape codes in static tables
#         - No environment detection on hot path (detection runs
#           once at module load)
#         - No template-literal tagged-function support (chalk has
#           this; kleur doesn't, saving parsing overhead)
#      Compare:
#         * chalk R528:        feature-rich, slower, larger
#         * picocolors:        even smaller than kleur, even faster
#         * ansis:              modern alternative, chalk-compatible
#         * colorette:         minimal, like picocolors
#      kleur is the FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library
#      positioned as a SPEED-FOCUSED chalk alternative.
#
#   2. ZERO RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES — kleur has no `dependencies` in
#      its package.json:
#
#          $ npm view kleur dependencies
#          {}
#
#      Compare chalk's dependency tree: chalk → ansi-styles +
#      supports-color → has-flag.  kleur eliminates those by
#      inlining their functionality.  Compare:
#         * chalk R528:    3 transitive deps (ansi-styles, supports-
#                            color, has-flag)
#         * picocolors:    0 deps (same as kleur)
#         * ora R524:      4+ deps (chalk + cli-cursor + log-symbols)
#         * blessed R536: 0 deps (also zero-dep)
#      kleur is the SECOND documented TS-Node CLI library with
#      ZERO runtime dependencies (after blessed R536 — which is
#      similarly old-school zero-dep).
#
#   3. METHOD-CALL CHAINING (NOT PROPERTY-CHAIN) — kleur uses
#      method CALLS rather than property access:
#
#          // chalk: property chain (getter-based)
#          chalk.red.bold.underline('text')
#
#          // kleur: method-call chain (function-based)
#          kleur.red().bold().underline('text')
#
#      The trailing parens on kleur are SIGNIFICANT — each call
#      returns a chainable styling object until you pass a string
#      to FINISH the chain:
#
#          kleur.red().bold()('hello')     // method-call style
#          kleur.red().bold().underline()('text')
#
#      OR via the `kleur/colors` subpath import that uses direct
#      ANSI-wrap functions (no chaining):
#
#          import { red, bold, underline } from 'kleur/colors';
#          console.log(red(bold(underline('text'))));
#
#      Compare:
#         * chalk R528:    property chain via JavaScript getters
#         * picocolors:    function nesting only (no chain)
#         * ansis:         supports both property chain AND nesting
#      kleur is the FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library with
#      method-call-chain styling.
#
#   4. SUBPATH IMPORTS FOR CHERRY-PICKING — kleur supports
#      importing only specific colors via subpath imports:
#
#          import { red, green, blue } from 'kleur/colors';
#          // Bundles only red, green, blue (not the chain object)
#
#          // Compare full import (includes chain object):
#          import kleur from 'kleur';
#          // Bundles entire kleur library
#
#      The `kleur/colors` subpath is TREE-SHAKEABLE — Vite/Rollup/
#      esbuild can eliminate unused color functions at build time.
#      Compare chalk R528 (entire library imported, not tree-
#      shakeable due to property-chain design).  FIRST documented
#      TS-Node CLI library with tree-shakeable subpath imports.
#
#   5. BROWSER-COMPATIBLE — kleur works in browsers without
#      polyfills:
#
#          import { red, green } from 'kleur/colors';
#          // Works in browser console (some browsers render ANSI)
#
#      Compare chalk R528 (browser-incompatible without manual
#      polyfills for process.stdout.isTTY).  FIRST documented
#      TS-Node CLI library that works unmodified in browsers.
#
# kleur's relationship to other documented TS-Node CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like chalk R528             — terminal coloring (same axis,
#                                    same API style — both chainable)
#   * Like ora R524                — uses chalk internally; kleur
#                                    is a drop-in chalk replacement
#                                    that some ora alternatives use
#   * Unlike chalk R528             — METHOD-CALL chains (not
#                                    property chains), zero deps,
#                                    subpath tree-shakeable, browser-
#                                    compatible
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    lexopt R534 (minimalist alternative to clap;
#                     same SPEED+SIZE design philosophy)
#         * Go:      not yet documented (Go's "minimalist" libraries
#                     tend to be stdlib `flag` rather than reaction-
#                     libraries against major projects)
#     The MINIMALIST-ALTERNATIVE pair (R534 lexopt for Rust argv
#     parsing + R548 kleur for TS-Node coloring) is now documented
#     across two languages.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE lighthouse-parade CLI — sade + kleur Composition
#
# lighthouse-parade's argv parser is lukeed/sade (same author as
# kleur — sade is Luke Edwards's minimalist sade CLI argv parser
# that's also used by 100+ npm packages):
#
#     import sade from 'sade';
#     import * as kleur from 'kleur/colors';
#
#     const symbols = {
#         error: kleur.red('✖'),
#         success: kleur.green('✔'),
#     };
#
#     sade('lighthouse-parade <url> [dataDirectory]', true)
#         .version(version)
#         .describe('Crawls the site at the provided URL...')
#         .option('--ignore-robots',
#                  "Crawl pages even if listed in robots.txt", false)
#         .option('--crawler-user-agent', '...')
#         .option('--lighthouse-concurrency',
#                  'Max number of lighthouse reports', os.cpus().length-1)
#         .option('--max-crawl-depth',
#                  'Maximum depth of crawled links')
#         .option('--include-path-glob',
#                  'Glob (in quotes) for paths to match')
#         .option('--exclude-path-glob',
#                  'Glob (in quotes) for paths to exclude')
#         .action((url, dataDirectory, options) => { ... })
#         .parse(process.argv);
#
# sade + kleur is a common lukeed-stack combination — both
# minimalist, both zero-dep, both speed-focused.  lighthouse-parade
# also uses log-update for progress display + the official Google
# lighthouse Node.js library for the actual audits.
#
# Distinct from every other documented TS-Node CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. SPEED-FIRST DESIGN — Every other documented TS-Node coloring
#      library prioritizes features (chalk) or zero-cost
#      abstractions (picocolors).  kleur prioritizes BENCHMARK
#      SPEED — 2-3x faster than chalk on the hot path.  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node CLI library with explicit speed-first
#      design.
#
#   2. ZERO RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES — Every other documented TS-Node
#      coloring library has at least 3 transitive dependencies
#      (chalk's ansi-styles + supports-color + has-flag).  kleur
#      has ZERO deps.  SECOND documented TS-Node CLI library with
#      zero deps (after blessed R536).
#
#   3. METHOD-CALL CHAINING — Every other documented TS-Node
#      coloring library uses property-chain access (chalk's
#      `chalk.red.bold`) or nested function calls (picocolors'
#      `red(bold('text'))`).  kleur uses METHOD-CALL chaining
#      (`kleur.red().bold()('text')`).  FIRST documented TS-Node
#      CLI library with method-call-chain styling.
#
#   4. SUBPATH IMPORTS TREE-SHAKEABLE — Every other documented
#      TS-Node coloring library is imported as a whole.  kleur's
#      `kleur/colors` subpath enables Vite/Rollup/esbuild to
#      eliminate unused color functions.  FIRST documented TS-Node
#      CLI library with tree-shakeable subpath imports.
#
#   5. BROWSER-COMPATIBLE — Every other documented TS-Node CLI
#      library is Node.js-only (relies on process.stdout.isTTY or
#      similar).  kleur works unmodified in browsers (some
#      browsers render ANSI in console.log).  FIRST documented
#      TS-Node CLI library with native browser compatibility.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/cloudfour/lighthouse-parade/blob/main/src/cli.ts
# sade .option/.action chain.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '--ignore-robots[crawl pages even if listed in robots.txt]' \
    '--crawler-user-agent=[user agent string for the crawler]:user-agent:' \
    '--lighthouse-concurrency=[max concurrent Lighthouse reports (default cpus-1)]:count:' \
    '--max-crawl-depth=[max crawl link depth (1=entry only)]:depth:' \
    '*--include-path-glob=[glob for paths to include (repeatable)]:glob:' \
    '*--exclude-path-glob=[glob for paths to exclude (repeatable)]:glob:' \
    '1:URL to crawl:' \
    '2:data directory:_directories' \
    && ret=0

return ret
